{"id": 231263370, "title": "Judge set to sentence Trump flags Facebook post claiming knowledge of verdict", "text": "Judge who is set to sentence Trump flags a random Facebook post that claimed to have an advance knowledge of the guilty verdict in the case. Justice Juan Merchan wrote a letter to prosecutors and the former president's defence team stating that \"the court became aware of a comment\" on the court's Facebook page. \"Today, the Court became aware of a comment that was posted on the Unified Court System\u2019s public Facebook page and which I now bring to your attention,\" the judge wrote in his short letter. The comment was made by a user named Michael Anderson posted under an unrelated post on the New York court system\u2019s Facebook page from May 29. READ MORE: Donald Trump gives update on son Barron's college plans days after trial ends It read: \"My cousin is a juror and says Trump is getting convicted. Thank you folks for all your hard work!!!\" It was made by a now-deleted account that regularly trolls the social media pages of the New York court system. Justice Juan did not indicate whether the post had been investigated or whether officials suspect any wrongdoing. Former federal prosecutor and NBC News contributor Joyce Alene said that Judge Merchan would be \u201csmart to advise the parties [and] hold a hearing on the record to resolve this.\u201d \"If it\u2019s someone posting with no basis for it as it appears, the record will be clear \u2026 and if there\u2019s something to it, good to get it out [and] do justice,\" she added. READ MORE: Donald Trump's 34 felony convictions shake up 2024 presidential race dynamics Moreover, the Manhattan District Attorney's Office and Todd Blanche, Trump's lead attorney, did not respond to requests for comment. Donald Trump was convicted of 34 felonies in the hush money case in New York City on 30 May, and is due to get sentenced on 11 July, a mere four days before the expected kick-off of the Republican National Convention in Milwaukee. It was a panel of 12 Manhattan jurors who came to a decision after a six-week trial with testimonies by 22 witnesses including Stormy Daniels, whose alleged sexual encounter with the former president was at the centre of the case. Click here to follow the Mirror UK on Google News to stay up to date with all the latest news, sports and entertainment stories. Each charge of falsifying business records could potentially result in up to four years of prison time, however, it's still unclear whether prosecutors will push for imprisonment. It remains equally uncertain if the judge, who had previously cautioned about possible jail time for violations of the gag order during the trial, would enforce such a penalty upon request. After the trial, Trump stood outside the courthouse and slammed the proceedings, saying: \"The real verdict is going to be Nov. 5 by the people,\" referring to Election Day. \"This is long from over.\"", "summary": "Justice Juan Merchan is set to sentence former US president, Donald Trump next month following his conviction over the hush-money payments made to porn star Stormy Daniels", "url": "https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/us-news/judge-set-sentence-trump-flags-32988472", "image": "https://i2-prod.mirror.co.uk/incoming/article32988336.ece/ALTERNATES/s1200/2_Jury-Finds-Former-President-Donald-Trump-Guilty-On-All-34-Counts-In-Hush-Money-Trial.jpg", "video": null, "publish_date": "2024-06-08 14:05:52", "author": "Rashi Agarwal,Rashi-Agarwal", "authors": ["Rashi Agarwal", "Rashi-Agarwal"], "language": "en", "catgory": "politics", "source_country": "GB", "sentiment": -0.312}